# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tissue-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis is a normal and vital process in growth and development, as well as in wound healing and in the formation of granulation tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] However, it is also a fundamental step in the transition of tumors from a benign to malignant state, leading to the use of angiogenesis inhibitors in the treatment of cancer.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The essential role of angiogenesis in tumor growth was first proposed in 1971 by Judah Folkman, who described tumors as "hot and bloody," illustrating that, at least for many tumor types, flush perfusion and even hyperemia are characteristic.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Sprouting angiogenesis was the first identified form of angiogenesis and because of this, it is much more understood than intussusceptive angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] It occurs in several well-characterized stages.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The initial signal comes from tissue areas that are devoid of vasculature.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The hypoxia that is noted in these areas causes the tissues to demand the presence of nutrients and oxygen that will allow the tissue to carry out metabolic activities.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Because of this, parenchymal cells will secrete vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF-A) which is a proangiogenic growth factor.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] These biological signals activate receptors on endothelial cells present in pre-existing blood vessels.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Second, the activated endothelial cells, also known as **tip cells**, begin to release enzymes called proteases that degrade the basement membrane to allow endothelial cells to escape from the original (parent) vessel walls.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The endothelial cells then proliferate into the surrounding matrix and form solid sprouts connecting neighboring vessels.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The cells that are proliferating are located behind the tip cells and are known as **stalk cells**.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The proliferation of these cells allows the capillary sprout to grow in length simultaneously.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] As sprouts extend toward the source of the angiogenic stimulus, endothelial cells migrate in tandem, using adhesion molecules called integrins.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] These sprouts then form loops to become a full-fledged vessel lumen as cells migrate to the site of angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Sprouting occurs at a rate of several millimeters per day, and enables new vessels to grow across gaps in the vasculature.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] It is markedly different from splitting angiogenesis because it forms entirely new vessels as opposed to splitting existing vessels.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Intussusceptive angiogenesis, also known as *splitting angiogenesis*, is the formation of a new blood vessel by splitting an existing blood vessel into two.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Intussusception was first observed in neonatal rats.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] In this type of vessel formation, the capillary wall extends into the lumen to split a single vessel in two.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] There are four phases of intussusceptive angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] First, the two opposing capillary walls establish a zone of contact.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Second, the endothelial cell junctions are reorganized and the vessel bilayer is perforated to allow growth factors and cells to penetrate into the lumen.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Third, a core is formed between the 2 new vessels at the zone of contact that is filled with pericytes and myofibroblasts.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] These cells begin laying collagen fibers into the core to provide an extracellular matrix for growth of the vessel lumen.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Finally, the core is fleshed out with no alterations to the basic structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Intussusception is important because it is a reorganization of existing cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] It allows a vast increase in the number of capillaries without a corresponding increase in the number of endothelial cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This is especially important in embryonic development as there are not enough resources to create a rich microvasculature with new cells every time a new vessel develops.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Coalescent angiogenesis is a mode of angiogenesis, considered to be the opposite of intussusceptive angiogenesis, where capillaries fuse, or coalesce, to make a larger bloodvessel, thereby increasing blood flow and circulation.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Coalescent angiogenesis has extended out of the domain of embryology.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] It is assumed to play a role in the formation of neovasculature, such as in a tumor.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Mechanical stimulation of angiogenesis is not well characterized.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] There is a significant amount of controversy with regard to shear stress acting on capillaries to cause angiogenesis, although current knowledge suggests that increased muscle contractions may increase angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This may be due to an increase in the production of nitric oxide during exercise.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Nitric oxide results in vasodilation of blood vessels.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Beyond fluid shear stress, the water channel AQP1 contributes to the mechanical expansion of the cell membrane during migration.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] By facilitating localized water influx at the leading edge, AQP1 creates the hydrostatic pressure necessary to drive membrane protrusions, which is a critical physical step in the formation of new vascular sprouts.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Chemical stimulation of angiogenesis is performed by various angiogenic proteins e.g. integrins and prostaglandins, including several growth factors e.g.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The fibroblast growth factor (FGF) family with its prototype members FGF-1 (acidic FGF) and FGF-2 (basic FGF) consists to date of at least 22 known members.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Most are single-chain peptides of 16-18 kDa and display high affinity to heparin and heparan sulfate.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] In general, FGFs stimulate a variety of cellular functions by binding to cell surface FGF-receptors in the presence of heparin proteoglycans.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The FGF-receptor family is composed of seven members, and all the receptor proteins are single-chain receptor tyrosine kinases that become activated through autophosphorylation induced by a mechanism of FGF-mediated receptor dimerization.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Besides FGF-1, one of the most important functions of fibroblast growth factor-2 (FGF-2 or bFGF) is the promotion of endothelial cell proliferation and the physical organization of endothelial cells into tube-like structures, thus promoting angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] FGF-2 is a more potent angiogenic factor than VEGF or PDGF (platelet-derived growth factor); however, it is less potent than FGF-1.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] As well as stimulating blood vessel growth, aFGF (FGF-1) and bFGF (FGF-2) are important players in wound healing.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] They stimulate the proliferation of fibroblasts and endothelial cells that give rise to angiogenesis and developing granulation tissue; both increase blood supply and fill up a wound space/cavity early in the wound-healing process.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) has been demonstrated to be a major contributor to angiogenesis, increasing the number of capillaries in a given network.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Initial *in vitro* studies demonstrated bovine capillary endothelial cells will proliferate and show signs of tube structures upon stimulation by VEGF and bFGF, although the results were more pronounced with VEGF.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Upregulation of VEGF is a major component of the physiological response to exercise and its role in angiogenesis is suspected to be a possible treatment in vascular injuries.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] *In vitro* studies clearly demonstrate that VEGF is a potent stimulator of angiogenesis because, in the presence of this growth factor, plated endothelial cells will proliferate and migrate, eventually forming tube structures resembling capillaries.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] VEGF causes a massive signaling cascade in endothelial cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Mechanically, VEGF is upregulated with muscle contractions as a result of increased blood flow to affected areas.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The increased flow also causes a large increase in the mRNA production of VEGF receptors 1 and 2.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The increase in receptor production means muscle contractions could cause upregulation of the signaling cascade relating to angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] As part of the angiogenic signaling cascade, NO is widely considered to be a major contributor to the angiogenic response because inhibition of NO significantly reduces the effects of angiogenic growth factors.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] However, inhibition of NO during exercise does not inhibit angiogenesis, indicating there are other factors involved in the angiogenic response.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The angiopoietins, Ang1 and Ang2, are required for the formation of mature blood vessels, as demonstrated by mouse knock out studies.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Ang1 and Ang2 are protein growth factors which act by binding their receptors, Tie-1 and Tie-2; while this is somewhat controversial, it seems that cell signals are transmitted mostly by Tie-2; though some papers show physiologic signaling via Tie-1 as well.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Thus, they can initiate cell signaling when ligand binding causes a dimerization that initiates phosphorylation on key tyrosines.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Another major contributor to angiogenesis is matrix metalloproteinase (MMP).
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] MMPs help degrade the proteins that keep the vessel walls solid.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This proteolysis allows the endothelial cells to escape into the interstitial matrix as seen in sprouting angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Inhibition of MMPs prevents the formation of new capillaries.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] These enzymes are highly regulated during the vessel formation process because destruction of the extracellular matrix would decrease the integrity of the microvasculature.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Delta-like ligand 4 (Dll4) is a protein with a negative regulatory effect on angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Dll4 is a transmembrane ligand, for the notch family of receptors.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] There have been many studies conducted that have served to determine consequences of the Delta-like Ligand 4.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] One study in particular evaluated the effects of Dll4 on tumor vascularity and growth.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] In order for a tumor to grow and develop, it must have the proper vasculature.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The VEGF pathway is vital to the development of vasculature that in turn, helps the tumors to grow.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The combined blockade of VEGF and Dll4 results in the inhibition of tumor progression and angiogenesis throughout the tumor.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This is due to the hindrance of signaling in endothelial cell signaling which cuts off the proliferation and sprouting of these endothelial cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] With this inhibition, the cells do not uncontrollably grow, therefore, the cancer is stopped at this point. if the blockade, however, were to be lifted, the cells would begin their proliferation once again.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Class 3 semaphorins (SEMA3s) regulate angiogenesis by modulating endothelial cell adhesion, migration, proliferation, survival and the recruitment of pericytes.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Furthermore, semaphorins can interfere with VEGF-mediated angiogenesis since both SEMA3s and VEGF-A compete for neuropilin receptor binding at endothelial cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The relative expression levels of SEMA3s and VEGF-A may therefore be important for angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] An angiogenesis inhibitor can be endogenous or come from outside as drug or a dietary component.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis may be a target for combating diseases such as heart disease characterized by either poor vascularisation or abnormal vasculature.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Application of specific compounds that may inhibit or induce the creation of new blood vessels in the body may help combat such diseases.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The presence of blood vessels where there should be none may affect the mechanical properties of a tissue, increasing the likelihood of failure.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The absence of blood vessels in a repairing or otherwise metabolically active tissue may inhibit repair or other essential functions.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Several diseases, such as ischemic chronic wounds, are the result of failure or insufficient blood vessel formation and may be treated by a local expansion of blood vessels, thus bringing new nutrients to the site, facilitating repair.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Other diseases, such as age-related macular degeneration, may be created by a local expansion of blood vessels, interfering with normal physiological processes.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The modern clinical application of the principle of angiogenesis can be divided into two main areas: anti-angiogenic therapies, which angiogenic research began with, and pro-angiogenic therapies.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Whereas anti-angiogenic therapies are being employed to fight cancer and malignancies, which require an abundance of oxygen and nutrients to proliferate, pro-angiogenic therapies are being explored as options to treat cardiovascular diseases, the number one cause of death in the Western world.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] One of the first applications of pro-angiogenic methods in humans was a German trial using fibroblast growth factor 1 (FGF-1) for the treatment of coronary artery disease.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] There are still serious, unsolved problems related to gene therapy.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The most commonly occurring disorders in humans, such as heart disease, high blood pressure, diabetes and Alzheimer's disease, are most likely caused by the combined effects of variations in many genes, and, thus, injecting a single gene may not be significantly beneficial in such diseases.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] By contrast, pro-angiogenic protein therapy uses well-defined, precisely structured proteins, with previously defined optimal doses of the individual protein for disease states, and with well-known biological effects.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] On the other hand, an obstacle of protein therapy is the mode of delivery.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Oral, intravenous, intra-arterial, or intramuscular routes of protein administration are not always as effective, as the therapeutic protein may be metabolized or cleared before it can enter the target tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Cell-based pro-angiogenic therapies are still early stages of research, with many open questions regarding best cell types and dosages to use.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Cancer cells are cells that have lost their ability to divide in a controlled fashion.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] A malignant tumor consists of a population of rapidly dividing and growing cancer cells that progressively accrues mutations.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] However, tumors need a dedicated blood supply to provide the oxygen and other essential nutrients they require in order to grow beyond a certain size (generally 1–2 mm3).
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Tumors induce blood vessel growth (angiogenesis) by secreting various growth factors (e.g.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Growth factors such as bFGF and VEGF can induce capillary growth into the tumor, which some researchers suspect supply required nutrients, allowing for tumor expansion.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Unlike normal blood vessels, tumor blood vessels are dilated with an irregular shape.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Other clinicians believe angiogenesis really serves as a waste pathway, taking away the biological end products secreted by rapidly dividing cancer cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] In either case, angiogenesis is a necessary and required step for transition from a small harmless cluster of cells, often said to be about the size of the metal ball at the end of a ball-point pen, to a large tumor.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis is also required for the spread of a tumor, or metastasis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Single cancer cells can break away from an established solid tumor, enter the blood vessel, and be carried to a distant site, where they can implant and begin the growth of a secondary tumor.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Evidence now suggests the blood vessel in a given solid tumor may, in fact, be mosaic vessels, composed of endothelial cells and tumor cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This mosaicity allows for substantial shedding of tumor cells into the vasculature, possibly contributing to the appearance of circulating tumor cells in the peripheral blood of patients with malignancies.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The subsequent growth of such metastases will also require a supply of nutrients and oxygen and a waste disposal pathway.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Endothelial cells have long been considered genetically more stable than cancer cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This genomic stability confers an advantage to targeting endothelial cells using anti-angiogenic therapy, compared to chemotherapy directed at cancer cells, which rapidly mutate and acquire drug resistance to treatment.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Thus, endothelial cells are thought to be an ideal target for therapies against cancer..
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Currently, there have been multiple clinical trials using anti-angiogenic therapies in combination with other therapeutic agents (e.g chemotherapy for treatment of various cancers.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The mechanism of blood vessel formation by angiogenesis is initiated by the spontaneous dividing of tumor cells due to a mutation.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Angiogenic stimulators are then released by the tumor cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] These then travel to already established, nearby blood vessels and activates their endothelial cell receptors.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This induces a release of proteolytic enzymes from the vasculature.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] These enzymes target a particular point on the blood vessel and cause a pore to form.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This is the point where the new blood vessel will grow from.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The reason tumour cells need a blood supply is because they cannot grow any more than 2-3 millimeters in diameter without an established blood supply which is equivalent to about 50-100 cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Certain studies have indicated that vessels formed inside the tumor tissue are of higher irregularity and bigger in size, which is as well associated with poorer prognosis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis represents an excellent therapeutic target for the treatment of cardiovascular disease.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] It is a potent, physiological process that underlies the natural manner in which our bodies respond to a diminution of blood supply to vital organs, namely *neoangiogenesis*: the production of new collateral vessels to overcome the ischemic insult.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] A large number of preclinical studies have been performed with protein-, gene- and cell-based therapies in animal models of cardiac ischemia, as well as models of peripheral artery disease.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Reproducible and credible successes in these early animal studies led to high enthusiasm that this new therapeutic approach could be rapidly translated to a clinical benefit for millions of patients in the Western world with these disorders.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] A decade of clinical testing both gene- and protein-based therapies designed to stimulate angiogenesis in underperfused tissues and organs, however, has led from one disappointment to another.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] It may be necessary to present these proteins in a way that mimics natural signaling events, including the concentration, spatial and temporal profiles, and their simultaneous or sequential presentation with other appropriate factors.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Early experimental evidence that skeletal muscle contraction induces vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) expression came from studies using electrically stimulated muscle.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] (1995) demonstrated that electrically stimulated skeletal muscle exhibited significant upregulation of VEGF expression, establishing skeletal muscle fibers as an active source of angiogenic signaling.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This work preceded later exercise-training studies and contributed to the understanding of VEGF as a contraction-responsive factor involved in skeletal muscle angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis is generally associated with aerobic exercise and endurance exercise.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] While arteriogenesis produces network changes that enable a large increase in total flow, angiogenesis produces changes that enable greater nutrient delivery over a longer period.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Capillaries are designed to provide maximum nutrient delivery efficiency, so an increase in the number of capillaries allows the network to deliver more nutrients in the same amount of time.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] A greater number of capillaries also allows for greater oxygen exchange in the network.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] This is vitally important to endurance training, because it allows a person to continue training for an extended period of time.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] However, no experimental evidence suggests that increased capillarity is required in endurance exercise to increase the maximum oxygen delivery.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Overexpression of VEGF causes increased permeability in blood vessels in addition to stimulating angiogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] In wet macular degeneration, VEGF causes proliferation of capillaries into the retina.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Since the increase in angiogenesis also causes edema, blood and other retinal fluids leak into the retina, causing loss of vision.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis of vessels from the host body into an implanted tissue engineered constructs is essential.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Successful integration is often dependent on thorough vascularisation of the construct as it provides oxygen and nutrients and prevents necrosis in the central areas of the implant.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] PDGF has been shown to stabilize vascularisation in collagen-glycosaminoglycan scaffolds.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The first report of angiogenesis can be traced back to the book *A treatise on the blood, inflammation, and gun-shot wounds* published in 1794, where Scottish anatomist John Hunter's research findings were compiled.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] In his study, Hunter observed the growth process of new blood vessels in rabbits.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] However, he did not coin the term "Angiogenesis," which is now widely used by scholars.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Hunter also erroneously attributed the growth process of new blood vessels to the effect of an innate vital principle within the blood.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The term "angiogenesis" is believed to have emerged not until the 1900s.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] The inception of modern angiogenesis research is marked by Judah Folkman's report on the pivotal role of angiogenesis in tumor growth.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Quantifying vasculature parameters such as microvascular density has various complications due to preferential staining or limited representation of tissues by histological sections.
[src:tissue-engineering/angiogenesis] Recent research has shown complete 3D reconstruction of tumor vascular structure and quantification of vessel structures in whole tumors in animal models.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] 3D bioprinting generally follows three steps: pre-bioprinting, bioprinting, and post-bioprinting.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Pre-bioprinting is the process of creating a model that the printer will later create and choosing the materials that will be used.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] One of the first steps is to obtain a biopsy of the organ, to sample cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Common technologies used for bioprinting are computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] To print with a layer-by-layer approach, tomographic reconstruction is done on the images.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The now-2D images are then sent to the printer to be made.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Once the image is created, certain cells are isolated and multiplied.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] These cells are then mixed with a special liquefied material that provides oxygen and other nutrients to keep them alive.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] This aggregation of cells does not require a scaffold, and is required for placing in the tubular-like tissue fusion for processes such as extrusion.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In the second step, the liquid mixtures of cells, matrix, and nutrients known as bioinks are placed in a printer cartridge and deposited using the patients' medical scans.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] When a bioprinted pre-tissue is transferred to an incubator, this cell-based pre-tissue matures into a tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] 3D bioprinting for fabricating biological constructs typically involves dispensing cells onto a biocompatible scaffold using a successive layer-by-layer approach to generate tissue-like three-dimensional structures.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Artificial organs such as livers and kidneys made by 3D bioprinting have been shown to lack crucial elements that affect the body such as working blood vessels, tubules for collecting urine, and the growth of billions of cells required for these organs.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Without these components the body has no way to get the essential nutrients and oxygen deep within their interiors.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Given that every tissue in the body is naturally composed of different cell types, many technologies for printing these cells vary in their ability to ensure stability and viability of the cells during the manufacturing process.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Some of the methods that are used for 3D bioprinting of cells are photolithography, magnetic 3D bioprinting, stereolithography, and direct cell extrusion.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The post-bioprinting process is necessary to create a stable structure from the biological material.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] If this process is not well-maintained, the mechanical integrity and function of the 3D printed object is at risk.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] To maintain the object, both mechanical and chemical stimulations are needed.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] These stimulations send signals to the cells to control the remodeling and growth of tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In addition, in recent development, bioreactor technologies have allowed the rapid maturation of tissues, vascularization of tissues and the ability to survive transplants.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Bioreactors work in either providing convective nutrient transport, creating microgravity environments, changing the pressure causing solution to flow through the cells, or adding compression for dynamic or static loading.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Each type of bioreactor is ideal for different types of tissue, for example compression bioreactors are ideal for cartilage tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Researchers in the field have developed approaches to produce living organs that are constructed with the appropriate biological and mechanical properties.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] 3D bioprinting is based on three main approaches: biomimicry, autonomous self-assembly and mini-tissue building blocks.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The first approach of bioprinting is called biomimicry.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The main goal of this approach is to create fabricated structures that are identical to the natural structure that are found in the tissues and organs in the human body.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Biomimicry requires duplication of the shape, framework, and the microenvironment of the organs and tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The application of biomimicry in bioprinting involves creating both identical cellular and extracellular parts of organs.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] For this approach to be successful, the tissues must be replicated on a micro scale.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Therefore, it is necessary to understand the microenvironment, the nature of the biological forces in this microenvironment, the precise organization of functional and supporting cell types, solubility factors, and the composition of extracellular matrix.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The second approach of bioprinting is autonomous self-assembly.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] This approach relies on the physical process of embryonic organ development as a model to replicate the tissues of interest.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] When cells are in their early development, they create their own extracellular matrix building block, the proper cell signaling, and independent arrangement and patterning to provide the required biological functions and micro-architecture.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly demands specific information about the developmental techniques of the tissues and organs of the embryo.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] There is a "scaffold-free" model that uses self-assembling spheroids that subjects to fusion and cell arrangement to resemble evolving tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly depends on the cell as the fundamental driver of histogenesis, guiding the building blocks, structural and functional properties of these tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] It demands a deeper understanding of how embryonic tissues mechanisms develop as well as the microenvironment surrounded to create the bioprinted tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The third approach of bioprinting is a combination of both the biomimicry and self-assembly approaches, called mini tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Organs and tissues are built from very small functional components.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The mini-tissue approach takes these small pieces and arrange them into larger framework.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Akin to ordinary ink printers, bioprinters have three major components to them.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] These are the hardware used, the type of bio-ink, and the material it is printed on (biomaterials).
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Bio-ink is a material made from living cells that behaves much like a liquid, allowing people to 'print' it in order to create the desired shape.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] To make bio-ink, scientists create a slurry of cells that can be loaded into a cartridge and inserted into a specially designed printer, along with another cartridge containing a gel known as bio-paper.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In bioprinting, there are three major types of printers that have been used.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] These are inkjet, laser-assisted, and extrusion printers.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Inkjet printers are mainly used in bioprinting for fast and large-scale products.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] One type of inkjet printer, called drop-on-demand inkjet printer, prints materials in exact amounts, minimizing cost and waste.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Printers that use lasers provide high-resolution printing; however, these printers are often expensive.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Extrusion printers print cells layer-by-layer, just like 3D printing to create 3D constructs.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In addition to just cells, extrusion printers may also use hydrogels infused with cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Extrusion-based printing is a very common technique within the field of 3D printing which entails extruding, or forcing, a continuous stream of melted solid material or viscous liquid through a sort of orifice, often a nozzle or syringe.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] When it comes to extrusion based bioprinting, there are four main types of extrusion.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] These are pneumatic driven, piston driven, screw driven and eccentric screw driven (also known as progressing cavity pump).
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Each extrusion method has their own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Pneumatic extrusion uses pressurized air to force liquid bioink through a depositing agent.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Air filters are commonly used to sterilize the air before it is used, to ensure air pushing the bioink is not contaminated.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Piston driven extrusion uses a piston connected to a guide screw.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The linear motion of the piston squeezes material out of the nozzle.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Screw driven extrusion uses an auger screw to extrude material using rotational motion.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Screw driven devices allow for the use of higher viscosity materials and provide more volumetric control.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Eccentric screw driven systems allow for a much more precise deposition of low to high viscosity materials due to the self-sealing chambers in the extruder.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Once printed, many materials require a crosslinking step to achieve the desired mechanical properties for the construct, which can be achieved for example with the treatment of chemical agents or photo-crosslinkers.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Direct extrusion is one of the most common extrusion-based bioprinting techniques, wherein the pressurized force directs the bioink to flow out of the nozzle, and directly print the scaffold without any necessary casting.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The bioink itself for this approach can be a blend of polymer hydrogels, naturally derived materials such as collagen, and live cells suspended in the solution.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In this manner, scaffolds can be cultured post-print and without the need for further treatment for cellular seeding.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Some focus in the use of direct printing techniques is based upon the use of coaxial nozzle assemblies, or coaxial extrusion.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The coaxial nozzle setup enables the simultaneous extrusion of multiple material bioinks, capable of making multi-layered scaffolds in a single extrusion step.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The development of tubular structures has found the layered extrusion achieved via these techniques desirable for the radial variability in material characterization that it can offer, as the coaxial nozzle provides an inner and outer tube for bioink flow.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Indirect extrusion techniques for bioprinting rather require the printing of a base material of cell-laden hydrogels, but unlike direct extrusion contains a sacrificial hydrogel that can be trivially removed post-printing through thermal or chemical extraction.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The remaining resin solidifies and becomes the desired 3D-printed construct.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Laser-based bioprinting can be split into two major classes: those based on cell transfer technologies or photo-polymerization.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In cell transfer laser printing, a laser stimulates the connection between energy-absorbing material (e.g. gold, titanium, etc.) and the bioink.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] This 'donor layer' vaporizes under the laser's irradiation, forming a bubble from the bioink layer which gets deposited from a jet.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Photo-polymerization techniques rather use photoinitiated reactions to solidify the ink, moving the beam path of a laser to induce the formation of a desired construct.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Certain laser frequencies paired with photopolymerization reactions can be carried out without damaging cells in the material.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In this form of printing, plastic residues are melted down and individual layered in sections to create a desired shape.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Nylon and PVA are examples of biomaterials used in this method.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] This technique is most often used to design prototypes for prosthetics and cartilage construction.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Another form of bioprinting involves an inkjet printer, which is primarily used in biomedical settings.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] This method prints detailed proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Hydrogels are commonly selected as the bioink.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Cells can be printed on to a selected surface media to proliferate and ultimately differentiate.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] A drawback of this printing method is the ability of the bioinks such as hydrogels to clog the printing nozzle, due to their high viscosity.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Ideal inkjet bioprinting involves using a low polymer viscosity (ideally below 10 centipoise), low cell density (<10 million cells/mL), and low structural heights (<10 million cells/mL).
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] There are several other bioprinting techniques which are less commonly used.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Droplet-based bioprinting is a technique in which the bioink blend of cells and/or hydrogels are placed in droplets in precise positions.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Most common amongst this approach are thermal and piezoelectric-drop-on-demand techniques.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] This method of bioprinting is often used experimentally with lung and ovarian cancer models.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Thermal technologies use short duration signals to heat the bioink, inducing the formation of small bubbles which are ejected.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Piezoelectric bioprinting has short duration current applied to a piezoelectric actuator, which induces a mechanical vibration capable of ejecting a small globule of bioink through the nozzle.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] A significant aspect of the study of droplet-based approaches to bioprinting is accounting for mechanical and thermal stress cells within the bioink experience near the nozzle-tip as they are extruded.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Bioinks are essential components of the bioprinting process.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] They are composed of living cells and enzymatic supplements to nurture an environment that supports the biological needs of the printed tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The environment created by the bioink allows for the cell to attach, grow, and differentiate into its adult form.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Cell-encapsualting hydrogels are used in extrusion based bioprinting methods, while gelatin MethacryloylGelatin methacrylon (GelMA) and acellular comprised bioinks are most often used in tissue engineering techniques that require cross-linkage and precise structural integrity.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] It is essential for bioinks to help replicate the external cellular matrix environment that the cell would naturally occur in.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] 3D bioprinting can be used to reconstruct tissue from various regions of the body.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The precursor to the adoption of 3D printing in healthcare was a series of trials conducted by researchers at Boston Children's Hospital.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The team built replacement urinary bladders by hand for seven patients by constructing scaffolds, then layering the scaffolds with cells from the patients and allowing them to grow.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The trials were a success as the patients remained in good health 7 years after implantation, which led a research fellow named Anthony Atala, MD, to search for ways to automate the process.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Patients with end-stage bladder disease can now be treated by using bio-engineered bladder tissues to rebuild the damaged organ.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] This technology can also potentially be applied to bone, skin, cartilage and muscle tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Though one long-term goal of 3D bioprinting technology is to reconstruct an entire organ as well as minimize the problem of the lack of organs for transplantation.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] There has been little success in bioprinting of fully functional organs e.g. liver, skin, meniscus or pancreas.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Unlike implantable stents, organs have complex shapes and are significantly harder to bioprint.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] A bioprinted heart, for example, must not only meet structural requirements, but also vascularization, mechanical load, and electrical signal propagation requirements.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In 2022, the first success of a clinical trial for a 3D bioprinted transplant that is made from the patient's own cells, an external ear to treat microtia, was reported.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The limitations of 3D bioprinting are associated with physiologically irrelevant morphology and unsuccessful histological evaluation methods.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] 3D bioprinting contributes to significant advances in the medical field of tissue engineering by allowing for research to be done on innovative materials called biomaterials.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Some of the most notable bioengineered substances are usually stronger than the average bodily materials, including soft tissue and bone.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] These constituents can act as future substitutes, even improvements, for the original body materials.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In addition, the Defense Threat Reduction Agency aims to print mini organs such as hearts, livers, and lungs as the potential to test new drugs more accurately and perhaps eliminate the need for testing in animals.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Bioprinting can also be used for cultured meat.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In 2021, a steak-like cultured meat, composed of three types of bovine cell fibers was produced.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The Wagyu-like beef has a structure similar to original meat.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] This technology provides an alternative to natural meat harvesting methods if the livestock industry is plagued by disease.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] In addition, it provides a possible solution to reducing the environmental impact of the livestock industry.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The bioprinting of biofilms uses the same methods as other bioprinting.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Oftentimes, the biofilm begins with an extrusion of a polysaccharide to provide structure for biofilm growth.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] An example of one of these polysaccharides is alginate.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The alginate structure can have microbes embedded within the structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Hydrogels can also be used to assist in the formation of functional biofilms.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Biofilms are difficult to analyze in a laboratory setting due to the complex structure and the time it takes for a functional biofilm to form.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] 3D bioprinting biofilms allows us to skip certain processes and makes it easier to analyze functional biofilms.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Thickness of the biofilm being printed with change the functionality due to nutrient and oxygen diffusion.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Thicker 3D printed biofilms will naturally select for anaerobes for example.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Biofilms are capable of remediation in the natural environment which suggests there is potential in regards to the use of 3D bioprinted biofilm use in environmental remediation.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Microbes are able to degrade a large range of chemicals and metals and providing a structure for these microbes to flourish such as in biofilm structures is beneficial.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Artificial biofilms protect the microbes from the dangers of the environment while promoting signaling and overall microbial interactions.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] 3D bioprinting allows functional microorganisms to be placed in structures that provide mechanical stability and protects them from environmental conditions.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] The larger contact area provided by 3D printed structures compared to normal environmental structures provides more efficient removal of pollutants.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Bioprinting also has possible uses in the future in assisting in wastewater treatment and in corrosion control.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] When humans come in contact with environmental biofilms, it is possible for infections and long-term health hazards to occur.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Antibiotic penetration and expansion within a biofilm is an area of research which can benefit from bioprinting techniques, to further explore the effect of environmental biofilms on human health.
[src:tissue-engineering/bioprinting] Biofilm printing requires further research due to limited published data and complex protocols.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] With a wide variety of decellularization-inducing treatments available, combinations of physical, chemical, and enzymatic treatments are carefully monitored to ensure that the ECM scaffold maintains the structural and chemical integrity of the original tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Scientists can use the acquired ECM scaffold to reproduce a functional organ by introducing progenitor cells, or adult stem cells (ASCs), and allowing them to differentiate within the scaffold to develop into the desired tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The produced organ or tissue can be transplanted into a patient.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] In contrast to cell surface antibodies, the biochemical components of the ECM are conserved between hosts, so the risk of a hostile immune response is minimized.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Proper conservation of ECM fibers, growth factors, and other proteins is imperative to the progenitor cells differentiating into the proper adult cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The success of decellularization varies based on the components and density of the applied tissue and its origin.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The applications to the decellularizing method of producing a biomaterial scaffold for tissue regeneration are present in cardiac, dermal, pulmonary, renal, and other types of tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Complete organ reconstruction is still in the early levels of development.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Researchers are able to take the tissue from a donor or cadaver, lyse and kill the cells within the tissue without damaging the extracellular components, and finish with a product that is the natural ECM scaffold that has the same physical and biochemical functions of the natural tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] After acquiring the ECM scaffold, scientists can recellularize the tissue with potent stem or progenitor cells that will differentiate into the original type of tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] By removing the cells from a donor tissue, the immunogenic antibodies from the donor will be removed.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The progenitor cells can be taken from the host, therefore they will not have an adverse response to the tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] This process of decellularizing tissues and organs is still being developed, but the exact process of taking a tissue from a donor and removing all the cellular components is considered to be the decellularization process.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The steps to go from a decellularized ECM scaffold to a functional organ is under the umbrella of recellularization.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Because of the diverse applications of tissue in the human body, decellularization techniques have to be tailored to the specific tissue being exercised on.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The researched methods of decellularization include physical, chemical, and enzymatic treatments.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Though some methods are more commonly used, the exact combination of treatments is variable based on the tissue's origin and what it is needed for.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] As far as introducing the different liquidized chemicals and enzymes to an organ or tissue, perfusion and immersion decellularization techniques have been used.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Perfusion decellularization is applicable when an extensive vasculature system is present in the organ or tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] It is crucial for the ECM scaffold to be decellularized at all levels, and evenly throughout the structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Because of this requirement, vascularized tissues can have chemicals and enzymes perfused through the present arteries, veins, and capillaries.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Under this mechanism and proper physiological conditions, treatments can diffuse equally to all of the cells within the organ.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The treatments can be removed through the veins at the end of the process.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Cardiac and pulmonary decellularization often uses this process of decellularization to introduce the treatments because of their heavily vascularized networks.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Immersion decellularization is accomplished through the submersion of a tissue in chemical and enzymatic treatments.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] This process is more easily accomplished than perfusion, but is limited to thin tissues with a limited vascular system.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The most common physical methods used to lyse, kill, and remove cells from the matrix of a tissue through the use of temperature, force and pressure, and electrical disruption.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Temperature methods are often used in a rapid freeze-thaw mechanism.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] By quickly freezing a tissue, microscopic ice crystals form around the plasma membrane and the cell is lysed.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] After lysing the cells, the tissue can be further exposed to liquidized chemicals that degrade and wash out the undesirable components.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Temperature methods conserve the physical structure of the ECM scaffold, but are best handled by thick, strong tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Direct force of pressure to a tissue will guarantee disruption of the ECM structure, so pressure is commonly used.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Pressure decellularization involves the controlled use of hydrostatic pressure applied to a tissue or organ.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] This is done best at high temperatures to avoid unmonitored ice crystal formation that could damage the scaffold.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Electrical disruption of the plasma membrane is another option to lyse the cells housed in a tissue or organ.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] By exposing a tissue to electrical pulses, micropores are formed at the plasma membrane.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The cells eventually turn to death after their homeostatic electrical balance is ruined through the applied stimulus.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] This electrical process is documented as non-thermal irreversible electroporation (NTIRE) and is limited to small tissues and the limited possibilities of inducing an electric current *in vivo*.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The proper combination of chemicals is selected for decellularization depending on the thickness, extracellular matrix composition, and intended use of the tissue or organ.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] For example, enzymes would not be used on a collagenous tissue because they disrupt the connective tissue fibers.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] However, when collagen is not present in a high concentration or needed in the tissue, enzymes can be a viable option for decellularization.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The chemicals used to kill and remove the cells include acids, alkaline treatments, ionic detergents, non-ionic detergents, and zwitterionic detergents.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The ionic detergent, sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS), is commonly used because of its high efficacy for lysing cells without significant damage to the ECM.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Detergents act effectively to lyse the cell membrane and expose the contents to further degradation.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] After SDS lyses the cell membrane, endonucleases and exonucleases degrade the genetic contents, while other components of the cell are solubilized and washed out of the matrix.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] SDS is commonly used even though it has a tendency to slightly disrupt the ECM structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Alkaline and acid treatments can be effective companions with an SDS treatment due to their ability to degrade nucleic acids and solubilize cytoplasmic inclusions.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The most well known non-ionic detergent is Triton X-100, which is popular because of its ability to disrupt lipid-lipid and lipid-protein interactions.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Triton X-100 does not disrupt protein-protein interactions, which is beneficial to keeping the ECM intact.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] EDTA is a chelating agent that binds calcium, which is a necessary component for proteins to interact with one another.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] By making calcium unavailable, EDTA prevents the integral proteins between cells from binding to one another.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] EDTA is often used with trypsin, an enzyme that acts as a protease to cleave the already existing bonds between integral proteins of neighboring cells within a tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Together, the EDTA-Trypsin combination make a good team for decellularizing tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Enzymes used in decellularization treatments are used to break the bonds and interactions between nucleic acids, interacting cells through neighboring proteins, and other cellular components.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Lipases, thermolysin, galactosidase, nucleases, and trypsin have all been used in the removal of cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] After a cell is lysed with a detergent, acid, physical pressure, etc., endonucleases and exonucleases can begin the degradation of the genetic material.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Endonucleases cleave DNA and RNA in the middle of sequences.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Benzoase, an endonuclease, produces multiple small nuclear fragments that can be further degraded and removed from the ECM scaffold.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Exonucleases act at the end of DNA sequences to cleave the phosphodiester bonds and further degrade the nucleic acid sequences.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Enzymes such as trypsin act as proteases that cleave the interactions between proteins.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Although trypsin can have adverse effects of collagen and elastin fibers of the ECM, using it in a time-sensitive manner controls any potential damage it could cause on the extracellular fibers.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Dispase is used to prevent undesired aggregation of cells, which is beneficial in promoting their separating from the ECM scaffold.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Experimentation has shown dispase to be most effective on the surface of a thin tissue, such as a lung in pulmonary tissue regeneration.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] To successfully remove deep cells of a tissue with dispase, mechanical agitation is often included in the process.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Collagenase is only used when the ECM scaffold product does not require an intact collagen structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Lipases are commonly used when decellularized skin grafts are needed.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Lipase acids function in decellularizing dermal tissues through delipidation and cleaving the interactions between heavily lipidized cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The enzyme, α-galactosidase is a relevant treatment when removing the Gal epitope antigen from cell surfaces.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] A natural ECM scaffold provides the necessary physical and biochemical environment to facilitate the growth and specialization of potent progenitor and stem cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Acellular matrices have been isolated *in vitro* and *in vivo* in a number of different tissues and organs.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Decellularized ECM can be used to prepare bio-ink for 3D bioprinting.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The most applicable success from decellularized tissues has come from symmetrical tissues that have less specialization, such as bone and dermal grafts; however, research and success are ongoing at the organ level.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Acellular dermal matrices have been successful in a number of different applications.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] For example, skin grafts are used in cosmetic surgery and burn care.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The decellularized skin graft provides mechanical support to the damaged area while supporting the development of host-derived connective tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Cardiac tissue has clinical success in developing human valves from natural ECM matrices.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] A technique known as the Ross procedure uses an acellular heart valve to replace a defective valve, allowing native cells to repopulate a newly functioning valve.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Decellularized allografts have been critical in bone grafts that function in bone reconstruction and replacing of deformed bones in patients.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The limits to myocardial tissue engineering come from the ability to immediately perfuse and seed and implemented heart into a patient.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Though the ECM scaffold maintains the protein and growth factors of the natural tissue, the molecular level specialization has not yet been harnessed by researchers using decellularized heart scaffolds.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Better success at using a whole organ from decellularization techniques has been found in pulmonary research.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Scientists have been able to regenerate whole lungs *in vitro* from rat lungs using perfusion-decellularization.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] By seeding the matrix with fetal rat lung cells, a functioning lung was produced.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The *in vitro*-produced lung was successfully implemented into a rat, which attests to the possibilities of translating an *in vitro* produced organ into a patient.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Other success for decellularization has been found in small intestinal submucosa (SIS), renal, hepatic, and pancreatic engineering.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Because it is a thin material, the SIS matrix can be decellularized through immersing the tissue in chemical and enzymatic treatments.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Renal tissue engineering is still developing, but cadaveric kidney matrices have been able to support development of potent fetal kidney cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Pancreatic engineering is a testament to the molecular specificity of organs.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] Scientists have not yet been able to produce an entirely functioning pancreas, but they have had success in producing an organ that functions at specific segments.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] For example, diabetes in rats was shown to decrease by seeding a pancreatic matrix at specific sites.
[src:tissue-engineering/decellularization] The future applications of decellularized tissue matrix is still being discovered and is considered one of the most hopeful areas in regenerative research.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Regenerative medicine also includes the possibility of growing tissues and organs in the laboratory and implanting them when the body cannot heal itself.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] When the cell source for a regenerated organ is derived from the patient's own tissue or cells, the challenge of organ transplant rejection via immunological mismatch is circumvented.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] This approach could alleviate the problem of the shortage of organs available for donation.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Some of the biomedical approaches within the field of regenerative medicine may involve the use of stem cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The ancient Greeks postulated whether parts of the body could be regenerated in the 700s BC.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Skin grafting, invented in the late 19th century, can be thought of as the earliest major attempt to recreate bodily tissue to restore structure and function.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Advances in transplanting body parts in the 20th century further pushed the theory that body parts could regenerate and grow new cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] These advances led to tissue engineering, and from this field, the study of regenerative medicine expanded and began to take hold.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] This began with cellular therapy, which led to the stem cell research that is widely being conducted today.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The first cell therapies were intended to slow the aging process.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] This began in the 1930s with Paul Niehans, a Swiss doctor who was known to have treated famous historical figures such as Pope Pius XII, Charlie Chaplin, and king Ibn Saud of Saudi Arabia.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Niehans would inject cells of young animals (usually lambs or calves) into his patients in an attempt to rejuvenate them.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In 1956, a more sophisticated process was created to treat leukemia by inserting bone marrow from a healthy person into a patient with leukemia.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] This process worked mostly due to both the donor and receiver in this case being identical twins.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Nowadays, bone marrow can be taken from people who are similar enough to the patient who needs the cells to prevent rejection.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The term "regenerative medicine" was first used in a 1992 article on hospital administration by Leland Kaiser.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Kaiser's paper closes with a series of short paragraphs on future technologies that will impact hospitals.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The term was brought into the popular culture in 1999 by William A.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Haseltine when he coined the term during a conference on Lake Como, to describe interventions that restore to normal function that which is damaged by disease, injured by trauma, or worn by time.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Haseltine was briefed on the project to isolate human embryonic stem cells and embryonic germ cells at Geron Corporation in collaboration with researchers at the University of Wisconsin–Madison and Johns Hopkins School of Medicine.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] He recognized that these cells' unique ability to differentiate into all the cell types of the human body (pluripotency) had the potential to develop into a new kind of regenerative therapy.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Later, Haseltine would go on to explain that regenerative medicine acknowledges the reality that most people, regardless of which illness they have or which treatment they require, simply want to be restored to normal health.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Designed to be applied broadly, the original definition includes cell and stem cell therapies, gene therapy, tissue engineering, genomic medicine, personalized medicine, biomechanical prosthetics, recombinant proteins, and antibody treatments.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] It also includes more familiar chemical pharmacopeia—in short, any intervention that restores a person to normal health.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In addition to functioning as shorthand for a wide range of technologies and treatments, the term "regenerative medicine" is also patient friendly.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] It solves the problem that confusing or intimidating language discourages patients.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The term regenerative medicine is increasingly conflated with research on stem cell therapies.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Some academic programs and departments retain the original broader definition while others use it to describe work on stem cell research.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In March 2000, Haseltine, Antony Atala, M.D., Michael D.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] West, Ph.D., and other leading researchers founded *E-Biomed: The Journal of Regenerative Medicine*.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The peer-reviewed journal facilitated discourse around regenerative medicine by publishing innovative research on stem cell therapies, gene therapies, tissue engineering, and biomechanical prosthetics.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The Society for Regenerative Medicine, later renamed the Regenerative Medicine and Stem Cell Biology Society, served a similar purpose, creating a community of like-minded experts from around the world.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In June 2008, at the Hospital Clínic de Barcelona, Professor Paolo Macchiarini and his team, of the University of Barcelona, performed the first tissue engineered trachea (wind pipe) transplantation.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Adult stem cells were extracted from the patient's bone marrow, grown into a large population, and matured into cartilage cells, or chondrocytes, using an adaptive method originally devised for treating osteoarthritis.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The team then seeded the newly grown chondrocytes, as well as epithelial cells, into a decellularised (free of donor cells) tracheal segment that was donated from a 51-year-old transplant donor who had died of cerebral hemorrhage.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] After four days of seeding, the graft was used to replace the patient's left main bronchus.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] After one month, a biopsy elicited local bleeding, indicating that the blood vessels had already grown back successfully.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In 2009, the SENS Foundation was launched, with its stated aim as "the application of regenerative medicine – defined to include the repair of living cells and extracellular material in situ – to the diseases and disabilities of ageing".
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In 2012, Professor Paolo Macchiarini and his team improved upon the 2008 implant by transplanting a laboratory-made trachea seeded with the patient's own cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In 2016, Paolo Macchiarini was fired from Karolinska University in Sweden due to falsified test results and lies.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The TV-show Experimenten aired on Swedish Television and detailed all the lies and falsified results.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In China, institutes dedicated to regenerative medicine are run by the Chinese Academy of Sciences, Tsinghua University, and the Chinese University of Hong Kong, among others.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Current research in regenerative medicine spans a continuous spectrum from fundamental cell biology to clinical translational engineering, focusing on deciphering and manipulating the signaling pathways that govern tissue morphogenesis, cellular differentiation, and scarless wound healing.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Rather than merely managing chronic symptoms, active laboratory investigations aim to understand why adult mammalian tissues lose the regenerative capacities inherent in lower vertebrates and human embryonic states.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] A major bottleneck in ongoing research is solving the scalability of functional vascularization, as complex engineered tissues cannot survive past the limits of oxygen diffusion without an integrated capillary network.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Cardiovascular regenerative medicine focuses on repairing damaged myocardial tissue, heart valves, and peripheral blood vessels, primarily targeting ischemic heart disease and congenital heart defects.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Because adult mammalian cardiomyocytes possess highly restricted proliferative capacity, therapeutic strategies utilize engineered cardiac patches, cell-seeded hydrogels, and decellularized extracellular matrix (ECM) components to stimulate localized myocardial repair after a myocardial infarction.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Clinical and pre-clinical research focuses heavily on using induced pluripotent stem cell-derived cardiomyocytes (hiPSC-CMs) and vascular endothelial cells embedded within porous, biomimetic polymeric scaffolds to ensure functional electrical coupling and host tissue integration.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Lung tissue engineering focuses on developing functional respiratory structures to treat end-stage pulmonary diseases, such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), pulmonary fibrosis, and acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS).
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Due to the complex, highly vascularized three-dimensional architecture of the lung, which comprises over forty distinct cell types and a delicate alveolar-capillary basement membrane, whole-organ biofabrication typically relies on decellularized donor lung scaffolds.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] This process strips away immunogenic cellular material while preserving the native extracellular matrix geometry and mechanical compliance required for ventilation.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Research strategies prioritize the multi-lineage recellularization of these scaffolds using patient-specific induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) differentiated into alveolar epithelial cells (type I and II) and microvascular endothelial cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Additionally, biomimetic microfluidic platforms, or "lung-on-a-chip" models, are utilized to study cellular shear stress and gas-exchange dynamics, serving as precursors to transplantable bioartificial lung devices.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Musculoskeletal applications represent a commercially mature sector of tissue engineering, focusing on the repair of critical-sized bone defects, articular cartilage lesions, and volumetric muscle loss.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] For orthopedic bone regeneration, therapeutic approaches utilize osteoconductive and osteoinductive scaffolds composed of bioceramics (such as hydroxyapatite and beta-tricalcium phosphate), biodegradable polymers, or composite hydrogels.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] These matrices serve as physical frameworks that recruit endogenous mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) and promote osteogenesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] A critical challenge in bone tissue engineering is achieving adequate neovascularization within the core of large scaffolds to prevent core necrosis before host capillary ingrowth occurs.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Consequently, modern biomaterial designs often implement multi-scale porosity, integrating smaller voids for nutrient diffusion with macro-channels greater than 100 micrometers, to facilitate deep cellular infiltration, matrix mineralization, and functional host tissue integration.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Regenerative strategies within the central nervous system (CNS) and peripheral nervous system (PNS) address severe impairments caused by spinal cord injuries, ischemic strokes, and neurodegenerative disorders such as Parkinson's disease.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The therapeutic microenvironment of the adult brain and spinal cord is highly inhibitory to axon growth due to the formation of glial scars and chondroitin sulfate proteoglycans.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Neuroregeneration research utilizes injectable hydrogels, shear-thinning biomaterials, and electrospun guidance conduits to physically bridge lesion cavities.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Dermal regeneration involves the development of bioengineered skin substitutes and advanced wound dressings to treat deep third-degree burns, diabetic foot ulcers, and extensive chronic wounds.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Unlike traditional occlusive dressings, regenerative skin scaffolds provide a temporary, porous extracellular matrix analog that coordinates cellular ingress, granulation tissue formation, and re-epithelialization.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Commercially available matrices utilize decellularized human or bovine dermal matrices, synthetic biodegradable polymers (such as polycaprolactone), and naturally derived marine biomaterials, including acellular fish skin graphics rich in omega-3 fatty acids.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] These matrices are designed to modulate the localized inflammatory response, suppress bacterial colonization, and recruit host fibroblasts and keratinocytes to restore functional, vascularized skin tissue while minimizing scar formation.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Regenerative medicine has been studied by dentists to find ways that damaged teeth can be repaired and restored to obtain natural structure and function.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Dental tissues are often damaged due to tooth decay, and are often deemed to be irreplaceable except by synthetic or metal dental fillings or crowns, which requires further damage to be done to the teeth by drilling into them to prevent the loss of an entire tooth.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Researchers from King's College London have created a drug called Tideglusib that claims to have the ability to regrow dentin, the second layer of the tooth beneath the enamel which encases and protects the pulp (often referred to as the nerve).
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Animal studies conducted on mice in Japan in 2007 show great possibilities in regenerating an entire tooth.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Some mice had a tooth extracted and the cells from bioengineered tooth germs were implanted into them and allowed to grow.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The result were perfectly functioning and healthy teeth, complete with all three layers, as well as roots.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] These teeth also had the necessary ligaments to stay rooted in its socket and allow for natural shifting.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] They contrast with traditional dental implants, which are restricted to one spot as they are drilled into the jawbone.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] A person's baby teeth are known to contain stem cells that can be used for regeneration of the dental pulp after a root canal treatment or injury.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] These cells can also be used to repair damage from periodontitis, an advanced form of gum disease that causes bone loss and severe gum recession.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Research is still being done to see if these stem cells are viable enough to grow into completely new teeth.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Some parents even opt to keep their children's baby teeth in special storage with the thought that, when older, the children could use the stem cells within them to treat a condition.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Extracellular matrix materials are commercially available and are used in reconstructive surgery, treatment of chronic wounds, and some orthopedic surgeries; as of January 2017 clinical studies were under way to use them in heart surgery to try to repair damaged heart tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The use of fish skin with its natural constituent of omega 3, has been developed by an Icelandic company Kereceis.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Omega 3 is a natural anti-inflammatory, and the fish skin material acts as a scaffold for cell regeneration.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In 2016 their product *Omega3 Wound* was approved by the FDA for the treatment of chronic wounds and burns.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In 2021 the FDA gave approval for *Omega3 Surgibind* to be used in surgical applications including plastic surgery.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Though uses of cord blood beyond blood and immunological disorders is speculative, some research has been done in other areas.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Any such potential beyond blood and immunological uses is limited by the fact that cord cells are hematopoietic stem cells (which can differentiate only into blood cells), and not pluripotent stem cells (such as embryonic stem cells, which can differentiate into any type of tissue).
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Cord blood has been studied as a treatment for diabetes.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] However, apart from blood disorders, the use of cord blood for other diseases is not a routine clinical modality and remains a major challenge for the stem cell community.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] The potential use of developmental bioelectricity in regenerative medicine is under active investigation, with particular interest in future organ and limb regeneration guided by bioelectric stimulation.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Developmental bioelectricity refers to endogenous ion flows and voltage gradients across cell membranes (Vmem) in excitable (able to create an action potential) and non-excitable tissues that provide instructive cues for growth.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] These bioelectric states, set by ion channels and pumps, are propagated through gap-junction coupling and together with chemical gradients and physical forces they form long-range patterning circuits.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Through voltage-sensitive signalling pathways, changes in Vmem modulate gene expression and cell behaviours (proliferation, migration, differentiation), thereby shaping tissue growth and polarity.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Experiments in vertebrate and invertebrate models indicate that bioelectric cues can steer regeneration.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In Xenopus tadpoles, activating a proton pump (V-ATPase) that moves hydrogen ions out of cells is necessary for tail regrowth and can restore regeneration during a normally refractory stage; in adult Zebrafish, inhibiting the same pump impairs fin regrowth.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In Planarians, brief electrical perturbations can cause tail pieces to form heads (including two-headed animals) or to regenerate heads resembling other species.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] In adult frogs, a 24-hour treatment with a drug-delivering ‘BioDome’ device initiated long-term hindlimb regrowth with multi-tissue repair and functional recovery.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Proposed techniques combine pharmacological control of ion channels and gap junctions, optogenetic actuators to write Vmem patterns with light, and devices that condition the injury microenvironment or apply controlled direct-current fields.
[src:tissue-engineering/regenerative-medicine] Proposed tools include voltage-sensitive dyes, microelectrodes, and wearable or implantable stimulators.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] While most definitions of tissue engineering cover a broad range of applications, in practice, the term is closely associated with applications that repair or replace portions of or whole tissues (i.e. organs, bone, cartilage, blood vessels, bladder, skin, muscle etc.).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Often, the tissues involved require certain mechanical and structural properties for proper functioning.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The term has also been applied to efforts to perform specific biochemical functions using cells within an artificially created support system (e.g. an artificial pancreas, or a bio artificial liver).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The term *regenerative medicine* is often used synonymously with tissue engineering, although those involved in regenerative medicine place more emphasis on the use of stem cells or progenitor cells to produce tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In addition, Langer and Vacanti also state that there are three main types of tissue engineering: cells, tissue-inducing substances, and a cells + matrix approach (often referred to as a scaffold).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Tissue engineering has also been defined as "understanding the principles of tissue growth, and applying this to produce functional replacement tissue for clinical use".
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] A further description goes on to say that an "underlying supposition of tissue engineering is that the employment of natural biology of the system will allow for greater success in developing therapeutic strategies aimed at the replacement, repair, maintenance, or enhancement of tissue function".
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Developments in the multidisciplinary field of tissue engineering have yielded a novel set of tissue replacement parts and implementation strategies.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Among the major challenges now facing tissue engineering is the need for more complex functionality, biomechanical stability, and vascularization in laboratory-grown tissues destined for transplantation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The historical origin of the term is unclear as the definition of the word has changed throughout the past few decades.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The term first appeared in a 1984 publication that described the organization of an endothelium-like membrane on the surface of a long-implanted, synthetic ophthalmic prosthesis.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The first modern use of the term as recognized today was in 1985 by the researcher, physiologist and bioengineer Yuan-Cheng Fung of the Engineering Research Center.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] He proposed the joining of the terms tissue (in reference to the fundamental relationship between cells and organs) and engineering (in reference to the field of modification of said tissues).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The term was officially adopted in 1987.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] An understanding of the inner workings of human tissues may date back further than most would expect.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] As early as the Neolithic period, sutures were being used to close wounds and aid in healing.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Later on, societies such as ancient Egypt developed better materials for sewing up wounds such as linen sutures.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Around 2500 BC in ancient India, skin grafts were developed by cutting skin from the buttock and suturing it to wound sites in the ear, nose, or lips.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Ancient Egyptians often would graft skin from corpses onto living humans and even attempted to use honey as a type of antibiotic and grease as a protective barrier to prevent infection.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In the 1st and 2nd centuries AD, Gallo-Romans developed wrought iron implants and dental implants could be found in ancient Mayans.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] While these ancient societies had developed techniques that were way ahead of their time, they still lacked a mechanistic understanding of how the body was reacting to these procedures.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This mechanistic approach came along in tandem with the development of the empirical method of science pioneered by René Descartes.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Sir Isaac Newton began to describe the body as a "physiochemical machine" and postured that disease was a breakdown in the machine.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In the 17th century, Robert Hooke discovered the cell and a letter from Benedict de Spinoza brought forward the idea of the homeostasis between the dynamic processes in the body.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Hydra experiments performed by Abraham Trembley in the 18th century began to delve into the regenerative capabilities of cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] During the 19th century, a better understanding of how different metals reacted with the body led to the development of better sutures and a shift towards screw and plate implants in bone fixation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Further, it was first hypothesized in the mid-1800s that cell-environment interactions and cell proliferation were vital for tissue regeneration.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] As time progresses and technology advances, there is a constant need for change in the approach researchers take in their studies.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Tissue engineering has continued to evolve over centuries.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In the beginning people used to look at and use samples directly from human or animal cadavers.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Now, tissue engineers have the ability to remake many of the tissues in the body through the use of modern techniques such as microfabrication and three-dimensional bioprinting in conjunction with native tissue cells/stem cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] These advances have allowed researchers to generate new tissues in a much more efficient manner.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] For example, these techniques allow for more personalization which allow for better biocompatibility, decreased immune response, cellular integration, and longevity.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] There is no doubt that these techniques will continue to evolve, as we have continued to see microfabrication and bioprinting evolve over the past decade.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In 1960, Wichterle and Lim were the first to publish experiments on hydrogels for biomedical applications by using them in contact lens construction.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Work on the field developed slowly over the next two decades, but later found traction when hydrogels were repurposed for drug delivery.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In 1984, Charles Hull developed bioprinting by converting a Hewlett-Packard inkjet printer into a device capable of depositing cells in 2-D.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Three dimensional (3-D) printing is a type of additive manufacturing which has since found various applications in medical engineering, due to its high precision and efficiency.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] So far, scientists have been able to print mini organoids and organs-on-chips that have rendered practical insights into the functions of a human body.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Pharmaceutical companies are using these models to test drugs before moving on to animal studies.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] However, a fully functional and structurally similar organ has not been printed yet.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] A team at University of Utah has reportedly printed ears and successfully transplanted those onto children born with defects that left their ears partially developed.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Today hydrogels are considered the preferred choice of bio-inks for 3-D bioprinting since they mimic cells' natural ECM while also containing strong mechanical properties capable of sustaining 3-D structures.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Furthermore, hydrogels in conjunction with 3-D bioprinting allow researchers to produce different scaffolds which can be used to form new tissues or organs.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] 3-D printed tissues still face many challenges such as adding vasculature.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Meanwhile, 3-D printing parts of tissues definitely will improve our understanding of the human body, thus accelerating both basic and clinical research.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Among the hydrogels, Festigel, a thermo-reversible gelation polymer group of scaffolds have been reported with in vitro tissue engineering and in vivo wound healing efficiency in urethral stricture, periodontal regeneration beside holding potentials in transportation of tissues and cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Cells are one of the main components for the success of tissue engineering approaches.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Tissue engineering uses cells as strategies for creation/replacement of new tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Cells can be used alone or with support matrices for tissue engineering applications.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] An adequate environment for promoting cell growth, differentiation, and integration with the existing tissue is a critical factor for cell-based building blocks.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Manipulation of any of these cell processes create alternative avenues for the development of new tissue (e.g., cell reprogramming - somatic cells, vascularization).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Techniques for cell isolation depend on the cell source.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Centrifugation and apheresis are techniques used for extracting cells from biofluids (e.g., blood).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Whereas digestion processes, typically using enzymes to remove the extracellular matrix (ECM), are required prior to centrifugation or apheresis techniques to extract cells from tissues/organs.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Trypsin and collagenase are the most common enzymes used for tissue digestion.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] While trypsin is temperature dependent, collagenase is less sensitive to changes in temperature.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Autologous: The donor and the recipient of the cells are the same individual.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Cells are harvested, cultured or stored, and then reintroduced to the host.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] As a result of the host's own cells being reintroduced, an antigenic response is not elicited.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The body's immune system recognizes these re-implanted cells as its own, and does not target them for attack.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Autologous cell dependence on host cell health and donor site morbidity may be deterrents to their use.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Adipose-derived and bone marrow-derived mesenchymal stem cells are commonly autologous in nature, and can be used in a myriad of ways, from helping repair skeletal tissue to replenishing beta cells in diabetic patients.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Allogenic: Cells are obtained from the body of a donor of the same species as the recipient.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] While there are some ethical constraints to the use of human cells for in vitro studies (i.e. human brain tissue chimera development), the employment of dermal fibroblasts from human foreskin demonstrates an immunologically safe and thus a viable choice for allogenic tissue engineering of the skin.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Xenogenic: These cells are derived isolated cells from alternate species from the recipient.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] A notable example of xenogeneic tissue utilization is cardiovascular implant construction via animal cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Chimeric human-animal farming raises ethical concerns around the potential for improved consciousness from implanting human organs in animals.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Syngeneic or isogenic: These cells describe those borne from identical genetic code.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This imparts an immunologic benefit similar to autologous cell lines (see above).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Autologous cells can be considered syngenic, but the classification also extends to non-autologously derived cells such as those from an identical twin, from genetically identical (cloned) research models, or induced stem cells (iSC) as related to the donor.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Scaffolds are materials that have been engineered to cause desirable cellular interactions to contribute to the formation of new functional tissues for medical purposes.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Cells are often 'seeded' into these structures capable of supporting three-dimensional tissue formation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Scaffolds mimic the extracellular matrix of the native tissue, recapitulating the *in vivo* milieu and allowing cells to influence their own microenvironments.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In 2009, an interdisciplinary team led by the thoracic surgeon Thorsten Walles implanted the first bioartificial transplant that provides an innate vascular network for post-transplant graft supply successfully into a patient awaiting tracheal reconstruction.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] To achieve the goal of tissue reconstruction, scaffolds must meet some specific requirements.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] High porosity and adequate pore size are necessary to facilitate cell seeding and diffusion throughout the whole structure of both cells and nutrients.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Biodegradability is often an essential factor since scaffolds should preferably be absorbed by the surrounding tissues without the necessity of surgical removal.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Injectability is also important for clinical uses.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Recent research on organ printing is showing how crucial a good control of the 3D environment is to ensure reproducibility of experiments and offer better results.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Material selection is an essential aspect of producing a scaffold.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The materials utilized can be natural or synthetic and can be biodegradable or non-biodegradable.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Additionally, they must be biocompatible, meaning that they do not cause any adverse effects to cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The material needed for each application is different, and dependent on the desired mechanical properties of the material.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Tissue engineering of long bone defects for example, will require a rigid scaffold with a compressive strength similar to that of cortical bone (100-150 MPa), which is much higher compared to a scaffold for skin regeneration.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] There are a few versatile synthetic materials used for many different scaffold applications.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] One of these commonly used materials is polylactic acid (PLA), a synthetic polymer.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This is a polyester which degrades within the human body to form lactic acid, a naturally occurring chemical which is easily removed from the body.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Similar materials are polyglycolic acid (PGA) and polycaprolactone (PCL): their degradation mechanism is similar to that of PLA, but PCL degrades slower and PGA degrades faster.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] PLA is commonly combined with PGA to create poly-lactic-co-glycolic acid (PLGA).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This is especially useful because the degradation of PLGA can be tailored by altering the weight percentages of PLA and PGA: More PLA – slower degradation, more PGA – faster degradation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This tunability, along with its biocompatibility, makes it an extremely useful material for scaffold creation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Scaffolds may also be constructed from natural materials: in particular different derivatives of the extracellular matrix have been studied to evaluate their ability to support cell growth.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Protein based materials – such as collagen, or fibrin, and polysaccharidic materials- like chitosan or glycosaminoglycans (GAGs), have all proved suitable in terms of cell compatibility.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Among GAGs, hyaluronic acid, possibly in combination with cross linking agents (e.g. glutaraldehyde, water-soluble carbodiimide, etc.), is one of the possible choices as scaffold material.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Due to the covalent attachment of thiol groups to these polymers, they can crosslink via disulfide bond formation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The use of thiolated polymers (thiomers) as scaffold material for tissue engineering was initially introduced at the 4th Central European Symposium on Pharmaceutical Technology in Vienna 2001.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] As thiomers are biocompatible, exhibit cellular mimicking properties and efficiently support proliferation and differentiation of various cell types, they are extensively used as scaffolds for tissue engineering.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Furthermore thiomers such as thiolated hyaluronic acid and thiolated chitosan were shown to exhibit wound healing properties and are subject of numerous clinical trials.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Additionally, a fragment of an extracellular matrix protein, such as the RGD peptide, can be coupled to a non-bioactive material to promote cell attachment.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Another form of scaffold is decellularized tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This is a process where chemicals are used to extracts cells from tissues, leaving just the extracellular matrix.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This has the benefit of a fully formed matrix specific to the desired tissue type.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] However, the decellurised scaffold may present immune problems with future introduced cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] A number of different methods have been described in the literature for preparing porous structures to be employed as tissue engineering scaffolds.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Each of these techniques presents its own advantages, but none are free of drawbacks.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Molecular self-assembly is one of the few methods for creating biomaterials with properties similar in scale and chemistry to that of the natural *in vivo* extracellular matrix (ECM), a crucial step toward tissue engineering of complex tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Moreover, these hydrogel scaffolds have shown superiority in in vivo toxicology and biocompatibility compared to traditional macro-scaffolds and animal-derived materials.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] These techniques include all the approaches that have been successfully employed for the preparation of non-woven meshes of different polymers.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In particular, non-woven polyglycolide structures have been tested for tissue engineering applications: such fibrous structures have been found useful to grow different types of cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The principal drawbacks are related to the difficulties in obtaining high porosity and regular pore size.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Solvent casting and particulate leaching (SCPL) allows for the preparation of structures with regular porosity, but with limited thickness.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] First, the polymer is dissolved into a suitable organic solvent (e.g. polylactic acid could be dissolved into dichloromethane), then the solution is cast into a mold filled with porogen particles.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Such porogen can be an inorganic salt like sodium chloride, crystals of saccharose, gelatin spheres or paraffin spheres.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The size of the porogen particles will affect the size of the scaffold pores, while the polymer to porogen ratio is directly correlated to the amount of porosity of the final structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Once the porogen has been fully dissolved, a porous structure is obtained.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Other than the small thickness range that can be obtained, another drawback of SCPL lies in its use of organic solvents which must be fully removed to avoid any possible damage to the cells seeded on the scaffold.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] To overcome the need to use organic solvents and solid porogens, a technique using gas as a porogen has been developed.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] First, disc-shaped structures made of the desired polymer are prepared by means of compression molding using a heated mold.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The discs are then placed in a chamber where they are exposed to high pressure CO2 for several days.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The pressure inside the chamber is gradually restored to atmospheric levels.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] During this procedure the pores are formed by the carbon dioxide molecules that abandon the polymer, resulting in a sponge-like structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The main problems resulting from such a technique are caused by the excessive heat used during compression molding (which prohibits the incorporation of any temperature labile material into the polymer matrix) and by the fact that the pores do not form an interconnected structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This technique does not require the use of a solid porogen like SCPL.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] First, a synthetic polymer is dissolved into a suitable solvent (e.g. polylactic acid in dichloromethane) then water is added to the polymeric solution and the two liquids are mixed in order to obtain an emulsion.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Before the two phases can separate, the emulsion is cast into a mold and quickly frozen by means of immersion into liquid nitrogen.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The frozen emulsion is subsequently freeze-dried to remove the dispersed water and the solvent, thus leaving a solidified, porous polymeric structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] While emulsification and freeze-drying allow for a faster preparation when compared to SCPL (since it does not require a time-consuming leaching step), it still requires the use of solvents.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Moreover, pore size is relatively small and porosity is often irregular.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Freeze-drying by itself is also a commonly employed technique for the fabrication of scaffolds.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In particular, it is used to prepare collagen sponges: collagen is dissolved into acidic solutions of acetic acid or hydrochloric acid that are cast into a mold, frozen with liquid nitrogen and then lyophilized.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Similar to the previous technique, the TIPS phase separation procedure requires the use of a solvent with a low melting point that is easy to sublime.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] For example, dioxane could be used to dissolve polylactic acid, then phase separation is induced through the addition of a small quantity of water: a polymer-rich and a polymer-poor phase are formed.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Following cooling below the solvent melting point and some days of vacuum-drying to sublime the solvent, a porous scaffold is obtained.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Liquid-liquid phase separation presents the same drawbacks of emulsification/freeze-drying.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Electrospinning is a highly versatile technique that can be used to produce continuous fibers ranging in diameter from a few microns to a few nanometers.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In a typical electrospinning set-up, the desired scaffold material is dissolved within a solvent and placed within a syringe.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This solution is fed through a needle and a high voltage is applied to the tip and to a conductive collection surface.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The buildup of electrostatic forces within the solution causes it to eject a thin fibrous stream towards the oppositely charged or grounded collection surface.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] During this process the solvent evaporates, leaving solid fibers leaving a highly porous network.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This technique is highly tunable, with variation to solvent, voltage, working distance (distance from the needle to collection surface), flow rate of solution, solute concentration, and collection surface.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This allows for precise control of fiber morphology.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] On a **commercial** level however, due to scalability reasons, there are 40 or sometimes 96 needles involved operating at once.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The bottle-necks in such set-ups are: 1) Maintaining the aforementioned variables uniformly for all of the needles and 2) formation of "beads" in single fibers that we as engineers, want to be of a uniform diameter.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] By modifying variables such as the distance to collector, magnitude of applied voltage, or solution flow rate – researchers can dramatically change the overall scaffold architecture.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Historically, research on electrospun fibrous scaffolds dates back to at least the late 1980s when Simon showed that electrospinning could be used to produce nano- and submicron-scale fibrous scaffolds from polymer solutions specifically intended for use as *in vitro* cell and tissue substrates.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This early use of electrospun lattices for cell culture and tissue engineering showed that various cell types would adhere to and proliferate upon polycarbonate fibers.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] It was noted that as opposed to the flattened morphology typically seen in 2D culture, cells grown on the electrospun fibers exhibited a more rounded 3-dimensional morphology generally observed of tissues *in vivo*.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Because most of the above techniques are limited when it comes to the control of porosity and pore size, computer assisted design and manufacturing techniques have been introduced to tissue engineering.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] First, a three-dimensional structure is designed using CAD software.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The porosity can be tailored using algorithms within the software.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The scaffold is then realized by using ink-jet printing of polymer powders or through Fused Deposition Modeling of a polymer melt.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The study found the smaller the pore size paired with mechanical stress in a bioreactor (to induce in vivo-like conditions), the higher the cell viability in potential therapeutic functionality via decreasing recovery time and increasing transplant effectiveness.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In a 2012 study, Koch et al. focused on whether Laser-assisted BioPrinting (LaBP) can be used to build multicellular 3D patterns in natural matrix, and whether the generated constructs are functioning and forming tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] LaBP arranges small volumes of living cell suspensions in set high-resolution patterns.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The investigation was successful, the researchers foresee that "generated tissue constructs might be used for in vivo testing by implanting them into animal models" (14).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Gustafsson et al. demonstrated free‐standing, bioactive membranes of cm-sized area, but only 250 nm thin, that were formed by self‐assembly of spider silk at the interface of an aqueous solution.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The membranes uniquely combine nanoscale thickness, biodegradability, ultrahigh strain and strength, permeability to proteins and promote rapid cell adherence and proliferation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] They demonstrated growing a coherent layer of keratinocytes.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] These spider silk nanomembranes have also been used to create a static *in-vitro* model of a blood vessel.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] A persistent problem within tissue engineering is mass transport limitations.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Engineered tissues generally lack an initial blood supply, thus making it difficult for any implanted cells to obtain sufficient oxygen and nutrients to survive, or function properly.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Self-assembly methods have been shown to be promising methods for tissue engineering.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Self-assembly methods have the advantage of allowing tissues to develop their own extracellular matrix, resulting in tissue that better recapitulates biochemical and biomechanical properties of native tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Self-assembling engineered articular cartilage was introduced by Jerry Hu and Kyriacos A.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Athanasiou in 2006 and applications of the process have resulted in engineered cartilage approaching the strength of native tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Self-assembly is a prime technology to get cells grown in a lab to assemble into three-dimensional shapes.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] To break down tissues into cells, researchers first have to dissolve the extracellular matrix that normally binds them together.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Once cells are isolated, they must form the complex structures that make up our natural tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The air-liquid surface established by Faraday waves is explored as a template to assemble biological entities for bottom-up tissue engineering.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This liquid-based template can be dynamically reconfigured in a few seconds, and the assembly on the template can be achieved in a scalable and parallel manner.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Assembly of microscale hydrogels, cells, neuron-seeded micro-carrier beads, cell spheroids into various symmetrical and periodic structures was demonstrated with good cell viability.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Formation of 3-D neural network was achieved after 14-day tissue culture.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] It might be possible to print organs, or possibly entire organisms using additive manufacturing techniques.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] A recent innovative method of construction uses an ink-jet mechanism to print precise layers of cells in a matrix of thermo-reversible gel.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Endothelial cells, the cells that line blood vessels, have been printed in a set of stacked rings.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] When incubated, these fused into a tube.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This technique has been referred to as "bioprinting" within the field as it involves the printing of biological components in a structure resembling the organ of focus.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The device is presented in a TED talk by Dr.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Anthony Atala, M.D. the Director of the Wake Forest Institute for Regenerative Medicine, and the W.H.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Boyce Professor and Chair of the Department of Urology at Wake Forest University, in which a kidney is printed on stage during the seminar and then presented to the crowd.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] It is anticipated that this technology will enable the production of livers in the future for transplantation and theoretically for toxicology and other biological studies as well.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In 2015 Multi-Photon Processing (MPP) was employed for in vivo experiments by engineering artificial cartilage constructs.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] An ex vivo histological examination showed that certain pore geometry and the pre-growing of chondrocytes (Cho) prior to implantation significantly improves the performance of the created 3-D scaffolds.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The achieved biocompatibility was comparable to the commercially available collagen membranes.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The successful outcome of this study supports the idea that hexagonal-pore-shaped hybrid organic-inorganic micro-structured scaffolds in combination with Cho seeding may be successfully implemented for cartilage tissue engineering.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Recently, tissue engineering has advanced with a focus on vascularization.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Using Two-Photon Polymerization-based additive manufacturing, synthetic 3D microvessel networks are created from tubular hydrogel structures.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] These networks can perfuse tissues several cubic millimeters in size, enabling long-term viability and cell growth in vitro.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] This innovation marks a significant step forward in tissue engineering, facilitating the development of complex human tissue models.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] In 2013, using a 3-D scaffolding of Matrigel in various configurations, substantial pancreatic organoids was produced in vitro.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Clusters of small numbers of cells proliferated into 40,000 cells within one week.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The clusters transform into cells that make either digestive enzymes or hormones like insulin, self-organizing into branched pancreatic organoids that resemble the pancreas.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The cells are sensitive to the environment, such as gel stiffness and contact with other cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Individual cells do not thrive; a minimum of four proximate cells was required for subsequent organoid development.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Modifications to the medium composition produced either hollow spheres mainly composed of pancreatic progenitors, or complex organoids that spontaneously undergo pancreatic morphogenesis and differentiation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Maintenance and expansion of pancreatic progenitors require active Notch and FGF signaling, recapitulating in vivo niche signaling interactions.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The organoids were seen as potentially offering mini-organs for drug testing and for spare insulin-producing cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Aside from Matrigel 3-D scaffolds, other collagen gel systems have been developed.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Collagen/hyaluronic acid scaffolds have been used for modeling the mammary gland In Vitro while co-coculturing epithelial and adipocyte cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] The HyStem kit is another 3-D platform containing ECM components and hyaluronic acid that has been used for cancer research.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p01] Additionally, hydrogel constituents can be chemically modified to assist in crosslinking and enhance their mechanical properties.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In many cases, creation of functional tissues and biological structures *in vitro* requires extensive culturing to promote survival, growth and inducement of functionality.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In general, the basic requirements of cells must be maintained in culture, which include oxygen, pH, humidity, temperature, nutrients and osmotic pressure maintenance.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Tissue engineered cultures also present additional problems in maintaining culture conditions.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In standard cell culture, diffusion is often the sole means of nutrient and metabolite transport.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] However, as a culture becomes larger and more complex, such as the case with engineered organs and whole tissues, other mechanisms must be employed to maintain the culture, such as the creation of capillary networks within the tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Another issue with tissue culture is introducing the proper factors or stimuli required to induce functionality.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In many cases, simple maintenance culture is not sufficient.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Growth factors, hormones, specific metabolites or nutrients, chemical and physical stimuli are sometimes required.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] For example, certain cells respond to changes in oxygen tension as part of their normal development, such as chondrocytes, which must adapt to low oxygen conditions or hypoxia during skeletal development.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Others, such as endothelial cells, respond to shear stress from fluid flow, which is encountered in blood vessels.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Mechanical stimuli, such as pressure pulses seem to be beneficial to all kind of cardiovascular tissue such as heart valves, blood vessels or pericardium.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In tissue engineering, a bioreactor is a device that attempts to simulate a physiological environment in order to promote cell or tissue growth in vitro.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] A physiological environment can consist of many different parameters such as temperature, pressure, oxygen or carbon dioxide concentration, or osmolality of fluid environment, and it can extend to all kinds of biological, chemical or mechanical stimuli.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Therefore, there are systems that may include the application of forces such as electromagnetic forces, mechanical pressures, or fluid pressures to the tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] These systems can be two- or three-dimensional setups.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Bioreactors can be used in both academic and industry applications.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] General-use and application-specific bioreactors are also commercially available, which may provide static chemical stimulation or a combination of chemical and mechanical stimulation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Cell proliferation and differentiation are largely influenced by mechanical and biochemical cues in the surrounding extracellular matrix environment.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Bioreactors are typically developed to replicate the specific physiological environment of the tissue being grown (e.g., flex and fluid shearing for heart tissue growth).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This can allow specialized cell lines to thrive in cultures replicating their native environments, but it also makes bioreactors attractive tools for culturing stem cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] A successful stem-cell-based bioreactor is effective at expanding stem cells with uniform properties and/or promoting controlled, reproducible differentiation into selected mature cell types.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] There are a variety of bioreactors designed for 3D cell cultures.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] There are small plastic cylindrical chambers, as well as glass chambers, with regulated internal humidity and moisture specifically engineered for the purpose of growing cells in three dimensions.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The bioreactor uses bioactive synthetic materials such as polyethylene terephthalate membranes to surround the spheroid cells in an environment that maintains high levels of nutrients.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] They are easy to open and close, so that cell spheroids can be removed for testing, yet the chamber is able to maintain 100% humidity throughout.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This humidity is important to achieve maximum cell growth and function.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The bioreactor chamber is part of a larger device that rotates to ensure equal cell growth in each direction across three dimensions.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] QuinXell Technologies now under Quintech Life Sciences from Singapore has developed a bioreactor known as the TisXell Biaxial Bioreactor which is specially designed for the purpose of tissue engineering.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] It is the first bioreactor in the world to have a spherical glass chamber with biaxial rotation; specifically to mimic the rotation of the fetus in the womb; which provides a conducive environment for the growth of tissues.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Multiple forms of mechanical stimulation have also been combined into a single bioreactor.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Using gene expression analysis, one academic study found that applying a combination of cyclic strain and ultrasound stimulation to pre-osteoblast cells in a bioreactor accelerated matrix maturation and differentiation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The technology of this combined stimulation bioreactor could be used to grow bone cells more quickly and effectively in future clinical stem cell therapies.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] MC2 Biotek has also developed a bioreactor known as ProtoTissue that uses gas exchange to maintain high oxygen levels within the cell chamber; improving upon previous bioreactors, since the higher oxygen levels help the cell grow and undergo normal cell respiration.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Active areas of research on bioreactors includes increasing production scale and refining the physiological environment, both of which could improve the efficiency and efficacy of bioreactors in research or clinical use.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Bioreactors are currently used to study, among other things, cell and tissue level therapies, cell and tissue response to specific physiological environment changes, and development of disease and injury.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In 2013, a group from the University of Tokyo developed cell laden fibers up to a meter in length and on the order of 100 μm in size.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] These fibers were created using a microfluidic device that forms a double coaxial laminar flow.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Each 'layer' of the microfluidic device (cells seeded in ECM, a hydrogel sheath, and finally a calcium chloride solution).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The seeded cells culture within the hydrogel sheath for several days, and then the sheath is removed with viable cell fibers.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Various cell types were inserted into the ECM core, including myocytes, endothelial cells, nerve cell fibers, and epithelial cell fibers.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This group then showed that these fibers can be woven together to fabricate tissues or organs in a mechanism similar to textile weaving.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Fibrous morphologies are advantageous in that they provide an alternative to traditional scaffold design, and many organs (such as muscle) are composed of fibrous cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] An artificial organ is an engineered device that can be extra corporeal or implanted to support impaired or failing organ systems.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Bioartificial organs are typically created with the intent to restore critical biological functions like in the replacement of diseased hearts and lungs, or provide drastic quality of life improvements like in the use of engineered skin on burn victims.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] While some examples of bioartificial organs are still in the research stage of development due to the limitations involved with creating functional organs, others are currently being used in clinical settings experimentally and commercially.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) machines, otherwise known as heart and lung machines, are an adaptation of cardiopulmonary bypass techniques that provide heart and lung support.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] It is used primarily to support the lungs for a prolonged but still temporary timeframe (1–30 days) and allow for recovery from reversible diseases.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Robert Bartlett is known as the father of ECMO and performed the first treatment of a newborn using an ECMO machine in 1975.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Tissue-engineered skin is a type of bioartificial organ that is often used to treat burns, diabetic foot ulcers, or other large wounds that cannot heal well on their own.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Artificial skin can be made from autografts, allografts, and xenografts.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Autografted skin comes from a patient's own skin, which allows the dermis to have a faster healing rate, and the donor site can be re-harvested a few times.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Allograft skin often comes from cadaver skin and is mostly used to treat burn victims.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Lastly, xenografted skin comes from animals and provides a temporary healing structure for the skin.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] They assist in dermal regeneration, but cannot become part of the host skin.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Tissue-engineered skin is now available in commercial products.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Integra, originally used to only treat burns, consists of a collagen matrix and chondroitin sulfate that can be used as a skin replacement.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The chondroitin sulfate functions as a component of proteoglycans, which helps to form the extracellular matrix.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Integra can be repopulated and revascularized while maintaining its dermal collagen architecture, making it a bioartificial organ Dermagraft, another commercial-made tissue-engineered skin product, is made out of living fibroblasts.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] These fibroblasts proliferate and produce growth factors, collagen, and ECM proteins, that help build granulation tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Since the number of patients awaiting a heart transplant is continuously increasing over time, and the number of patients on the waiting list surpasses the organ availability, artificial organs used as replacement therapy for terminal heart failure would help alleviate this difficulty.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Artificial hearts are usually used to bridge the heart transplantation or can be applied as replacement therapy for terminal heart malfunction.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The total artificial heart (TAH), first introduced by Dr.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Demikhov in 1937, emerged as an ideal alternative.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Since then it has been developed and improved as a mechanical pump that provides long-term circulatory support and replaces diseased or damaged heart ventricles that cannot properly pump the blood, restoring thus the pulmonary and systemic flow.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Some of the current TAHs include AbioCor, an FDA-approved device that comprises two artificial ventricles and their valves, and does not require subcutaneous connections, and is indicated for patients with biventricular heart failure.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In 2010 SynCardia released the portable freedom driver that allows patients to have a portable device without being confined to the hospital.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] While kidney transplants are possible, renal failure is more often treated using an artificial kidney.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The first artificial kidneys and the majority of those currently in use are extracorporeal, such as with hemodialysis, which filters blood directly, or peritoneal dialysis, which filters via a fluid in the abdomen.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In order to contribute to the biological functions of a kidney such as producing metabolic factors or hormones, some artificial kidneys incorporate renal cells.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] There has been progress in the way of making these devices smaller and more transportable, or even implantable .
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] One challenge still to be faced in these smaller devices is countering the limited volume and therefore limited filtering capabilities.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Bioscaffolds have also been introduced to provide a framework upon which normal kidney tissue can be regenerated.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] These scaffolds encompass natural scaffolds (e.g., decellularized kidneys, collagen hydrogel, or silk fibroin), synthetic scaffolds (e.g., poly[lactic-co-glycolic acid] or other polymers), or a combination of two or more natural and synthetic scaffolds.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] These scaffolds can be implanted into the body either without cell treatment or after a period of stem cell seeding and incubation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In vitro and In vivo studies are being conducted to compare and optimize the type of scaffold and to assess whether cell seeding prior to implantation adds to the viability, regeneration and effective function of the kidneys.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Therefore, further studies involving larger animals and novel scaffolds, and more transparent reproduction of previous studies are advisable.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Biomimetics is a field that aims to produce materials and systems that replicate those present in nature.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In the context of tissue engineering, this is a common approach used by engineers to create materials for these applications that are comparable to native tissues in terms of their structure, properties, and biocompatibility.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Material properties are largely dependent on physical, structural, and chemical characteristics of that material.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Subsequently, a biomimetic approach to system design will become significant in material integration, and a sufficient understanding of biological processes and interactions will be necessary.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Replication of biological systems and processes may also be used in the synthesis of bio-inspired materials to achieve conditions that produce the desired biological material.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Therefore, if a material is synthesized having the same characteristics of biological tissues both structurally and chemically, then ideally the synthesized material will have similar properties.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This technique has an extensive history originating from the idea of using natural phenomenon as design inspiration for solutions to human problems.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Many modern advancements in technology have been inspired by nature and natural systems, including aircraft, automobiles, architecture, and even industrial systems.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Advancements in nanotechnology initiated the application of this technique to micro- and nano-scale problems, including tissue engineering.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This technique has been used to develop synthetic bone tissues, vascular technologies, scaffolding materials and integration techniques, and functionalized nanoparticles.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In 2018, scientists at Brandeis University reported their research on soft material embedded with chemical networks which can mimic the smooth and coordinated behavior of neural tissue.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The researchers presented an experimental system of neural networks, theoretically modeled as reaction-diffusion systems.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Within the networks was an array of patterned reactors, each performing the Belousov-Zhabotinsky (BZ) reaction.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] These reactors could function on a nanoliter scale.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The researchers state that the inspiration for their project was the movement of the blue ribbon eel.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The eel's movements are controlled by electrical impulses determined by a class of neural networks called the central pattern generator.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Central Pattern Generators function within the autonomic nervous system to control bodily functions such as respiration, movement, and peristalsis.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Qualities of the reactor that were designed were the network topology, boundary conditions, initial conditions, reactor volume, coupling strength, and the synaptic polarity of the reactor (whether its behavior is inhibitory or excitatory).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] A BZ emulsion system with a solid elastomer polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS) was designed.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Both light and bromine permeable PDMS have been reported as viable methods to create a pacemaker for neural networks.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The history of the tissue engineering market can be divided into three major parts.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The time before the crash of the biotech market in the early 2000s, the crash and the time afterward.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Most early progress in tissue engineering research was done in the US.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This is due to less strict regulations regarding stem cell research and more available funding than in other countries.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This leads to the creation of academic startups many of them coming from Harvard or MIT.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Examples are BioHybrid Technologies whose founder, Bill Chick, went to Harvard Medical School and focused on the creation of artificial pancreas.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Another example would be Organogenesis Inc. whose founder went to MIT and worked on skin engineering products.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Other companies with links to the MIT are TEI Biosciences, Therics and Guilford Pharmaceuticals.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The renewed interest in biotechnologies in the 1980s leads to many private investors investing in these new technologies even though the business models of these early startups were often not very clear and did not present a path to long term profitability.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Government sponsors were more restrained in their funding as tissue engineering was considered a high-risk investment.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In the UK the market got off to a slower start even though the regulations on stem cell research were not strict as well.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This is mainly due to more investors being less willing to invest in these new technologies which were considered to be high-risk investments.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Another problem faced by British companies was getting the NHS to pay for their products.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This especially because the NHS runs a cost-effectiveness analysis on all supported products.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Novel technologies often do not do well in this respect.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In Japan, the regulatory situation was quite different.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] First cell cultivation was only allowed in a hospital setting and second academic scientists employed by state-owned universities were not allowed outside employment until 1998.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Moreover, the Japanese authorities took longer to approve new drugs and treatments than there US and European counterparts.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] For these reasons in the early days of the Japanese market, the focus was mainly on getting products that were already approved elsewhere in Japan and selling them.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Contrary to the US market the early actors in Japan were mainly big firms or sub-companies of such big firms, such as J-TEC, Menicon and Terumo, and not small startups.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] After regulatory changes in 2014, which allowed cell cultivation outside of a hospital setting, the speed of research in Japan increased and Japanese companies also started to develop their own products.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Soon after the big boom, the first problems started to appear.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] There were problems getting products approved by the FDA and if they got approved there were often difficulties in getting insurance providers to pay for the products and getting it accepted by health care providers.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] For example, organogenesis ran into problems marketing its product and integrating its product in the health system.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This partially due to the difficulties of handling living cells and the increased difficulties faced by physicians in using these products over conventional methods.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Another example would be Advanced Tissue Sciences Dermagraft skin product which could not create a high enough demand without reimbursements from insurance providers.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Reasons for this were $4000 price-tag and the circumstance that Additionally Advanced Tissue Sciences struggled to get their product known by physicians.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The above examples demonstrate how companies struggled to make profit.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] This, in turn, lead investors to lose patience and stopping further funding.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In consequence, several Tissue Engineering companies such as Organogenesis and Advanced Tissue Sciences filed for bankruptcy in the early 2000s.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] At this time, these were the only ones having commercial skin products on the market.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The technologies of the bankrupt or struggling companies were often bought by other companies which continued the development under more conservative business models.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Examples of companies who sold their products after folding were Curis and Intercytex.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Many of the companies abandoned their long-term goals of developing fully functional organs in favor of products and technologies that could turn a profit in the short run.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Examples of these kinds of products are products in the cosmetic and testing industry.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In other cases such as in the case of Advanced Tissue Sciences, the founders started new companies.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In the 2010s the regulatory framework also started to facilitate faster time to market especially in the US as new centres and pathways were created by the FDA specifically aimed at products coming from living cells such as the Center for Biologics Evaluation and Research.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The first tissue engineering products started to get commercially profitable in the 2010s.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] In Europe, regulation is currently split into three areas of regulation: medical devices, medicinal products, and biologics.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Tissue engineering products are often of hybrid nature, as they are often composed of cells and a supporting structure.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] While some products can be approved as medicinal products, others need to gain approval as medical devices.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Derksen explains in her thesis that tissue engineering researchers are sometimes confronted with regulation that does not fit the characteristics of tissue engineering.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] New regulatory regimes have been observed in Europe that tackle these issues.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] An explanation for the difficulties in finding regulatory consensus in this matter is given by a survey conducted in the UK.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The authors attribute these problems to the close relatedness and overlap with other technologies such as xenotransplantation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] It can therefore not be handled separately by regulatory bodies.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Regulation is further complicated by the ethical controversies associated with this and related fields of research (e.g. stem cells controversy, ethics of organ transplantation).
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The same survey as mentioned above shows on the example of autologous cartilage transplantation that a specific technology can be regarded as 'pure' or 'polluted' by the same social actor.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] Two regulatory movements are most relevant to tissue engineering in the European Union.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] These are Directive 2004/23/EC on standards of quality and safety for the sourcing and processing of human tissues which was adopted by the European Parliament in 2004 and a proposed Human Tissue-Engineered Products regulation.
[src:tissue-engineering/tissue-engineering-p02] The latter was developed under the auspices of the European Commission DG Enterprise and presented in Brussels in 2004.
